  window.postData["rising"] = [{"_id":"54238b1eb589e44d020004e0","id":"2014/09/24/vine-update-vine-challenge","title":"Vine Challenge: Use the Newest Update to Create Cool Six-Second Videos","title_tag":null,"author":"Annie Park","post_date":"2014-09-25T03:25:16+00:00","post_date_rfc":"Thu, 25 Sep 2014 03:25:16 +0000","sort_key":"1xx09k","link":"http://mashable.com/2014/09/24/vine-update-vine-challenge/","content":{"plain":"Vine's latest update introduced a ton of new features, the biggest of which is probably video import. iOS users can now upload any video from their camera roll directly into the app, and trim longer ones down to the six-second limit.\n\nThis, of course, does not mean the good ol' days of #AllNaturalVines are over -- anything but! Vine allows a combination of outside videos and footage shot in-app, so really, it opens up doors to collaboration and more creativity.\n\nSee also: Hands On With the New Vine: 6-Second Videos Will Never Be the Same\n\nYou can also duplicate frames and mute the sound in individual clips, as well as preview every shot while still in shooting mode. And some of the best features happen to be things we didn't expect to see: a torch for lighting up dark rooms, a level to balance your shot, and focus lock and ghost mode on the front camera.\n\nFor this week's Mashable Vine Challenge, we're asking readers to use some (or all) of these new features to create cool six-second videos.\n\nWe played around with video import, the level and torch, and frame duplicating for our own example. The result: something unique and pretty trippy.\n\nUpload your Vines by Tuesday, Sept. 30, at 10 a.m. ET using the hashtag #LatestUpdate. We will choose our favorite submissions to revine, and feature on Mashable. We can't wait to see what you come up with!\n\nHave something to add to this story? Share it in the comments."},"shares":{"twitter":1062,"facebook":124,"linked_in":61,"google_plus":19,"pinterest":1,"total":1267},"comments_count":0,"image":"