  window.postData["hot"] = [{"_id":"5427084cb05f9d5424003795","id":"2014/09/27/google-doodle-16th-birthday","title":"Google Doodle Celebrates Its 16th Birthday","title_tag":null,"author":"Chelsea Stark","post_date":"2014-09-27T18:56:07+00:00","post_date_rfc":"Sat, 27 Sep 2014 18:56:07 +0000","sort_key":"1xxXM1","link":"http://mashable.com/2014/09/27/google-doodle-16th-birthday/","content":{"plain":"Happy sweet 16, Google Doodle!\n\nThe quirky art featured on the search giant's homepage celebrated its 16th birthday on Saturday with, appropriately, an animated Google Doodle. In it, the G in Google's logo measures the growth of the O and L.\n\nSee also: 8 Google Easter Eggs Worth the Extra Peep\n\nGoogle's unique art has celebrated a variety of people, events and causes over the years. Its topics have ranged from sci-fi show Doctor Who to iconic actress Audrey Hepburn, as well as social causes including International Women's Day, the Sochi Winter Olympics gay-rights controversy and the 50th anniversary of Martin Luther King Jr.'s \"I Have a Dream\" speech.\n\nOver the years, Google has become more technically ambitious with its Doodles, including an audio partnership with NPR radio program This American Life for Valentine's Day, a playable guitar in honor of Les Paul and a working Rubix cube. Also, let's not forget the Pac-Man Google Doodle that distracted us all from work in 2010.\n\nSo happy birthday, Google Doodle. Please keep delighting us for another 16 years and more. \n\nHave something to add to this story? Share it in the comments."},"shares":{"twitter":1134,"facebook":96,"linked_in":129,"google_plus":7,"total":1366},"comments_count":0,"image":"http://rack.1.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI3LzNjL2hhcHB5YmlydGhkLmU1MDVlLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTk1MHg1MzQjCmUJanBn/428731a6/225/happy-birthday.jpg","responsive_images":[{"image":"http://rack.2.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI3LzNjL2hhcHB5YmlydGhkLmU1MDVlLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTYzOHgzNjgjCmUJanBn/b13ec49c/225/happy-birthday.jpg","query":true,"size":"638x368#"},{"image":"http://rack.3.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI3LzNjL2hhcHB5YmlydGhkLmU1MDVlLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTEyNzZ4NzM2IwplCWpwZw/9bd5a289/225/happy-birthday.jpg","query":"(min-resolution: 1.5dppx)","size":"1276x736#"},{"image":"http://rack.1.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI3LzNjL2hhcHB5YmlydGhkLmU1MDVlLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTM1NngyMDUjCmUJanBn/ca7cf708/225/happy-birthday.jpg","query":"(max-width: 1160px)","size":"356x205#"},{"image":"http://rack.2.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI3LzNjL2hhcHB5YmlydGhkLmU1MDVlLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTcxMng0MTAjCmUJanBn/5146494e/225/happy-birthday.jpg","query":"(max-width: 1160px) and (min-resolution: 1.5dppx)","size":"712x410#"},{"image":"http://rack.3.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI3LzNjL2hhcHB5YmlydGhkLmU1MDVlLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTI4MHgxNTcjCmUJanBn/3866ff4a/225/happy-birthday.jpg","query":"(max-width: 480px)","size":"280x157#"},{"image":"http://rack.1.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI3LzNjL2hhcHB5YmlydGhkLmU1MDVlLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTU2MHgzMTQjCmUJanBn/2e233e72/225/happy-birthday.jpg","query":"(max-width: 480px) and (min-resolution: 1.5dppx)","size":"560x314#"}],"short_url":"http://on.mash.to/1uQWHIR","choice":false,"spotlight":false,"shortcode_data":{"see_also":[{"data-url":"http://mashable.com/2014/04/16/google-easter-eggs-3/"}],"wp_shortcode_manager":[{}]},"excerpt":"Happy sweet 16, Google Doodle!\r\n","show_sponsorship":true,"channel":"Tech","channel_link":"http://mashable.com/tech/"},{"_id":"5425ebebb589e40b090023a0","id":"2014/09/26/ello-facebook","title":"If Not Ello, Something Else: Facebook's 'Real Names' Policy Could Turn It Into Friendster","title_tag":null,"author":"Chris Taylor","post_date":"2014-09-26T22:42:41+00:00","post_date_rfc":"Fri, 26 Sep 2014 22:42:41 +0000","sort_key":"1xxEXU","link":"http://mashable.com/2014/09/26/ello-facebook/","content":{"plain":"Ello doesn't really work. \n\nThat much isn't surprising. The bare bones, ad-free, invite-only social network launched in March is still in beta, and evidently didn't anticipate becoming this hot this fast. \n\nThere isn't a working search function. I can't find my friends, which is about a basic a function as a social network needs to have. I have to login every time I use it. My Ello feed (I'm @futureboy, naturally) has nothing but a list of people accepting my invites. There's another part of the feed called \"noise,\" which basically looks like a cut-rate Pinterest.\n\nSee also: What's Up With Ello, the Anti-Facebook Social Network?\n\nSo why all the light and heat around Ello? Why is half of my Facebook feed suddenly taken up with friends announcing their Ello names, or posting stories about a service that obviously isn't ready for prime time? \n\nOn one level, it's a land grab. I don't want anyone else to get the @futureboy name, so of course I signed up. Early adopters are pretty annoying that way: We're never quite sure what the next big thing is, so we sign up for everything and purchase every gadget, for fear of being late to the party. Especially an invite-only party: There's nothing we like more than a velvet rope around a service.\n\nBut on a far more important level, it's a symptom of profound discomfort with Facebook. Early reports, as well as the anecdotal evidence of my Facebook feed, suggest that the Ello migration started because the LGBT community was justifiably irked by Facebook's \"real names\" policy. \n\n\"Real names\" means that if you're not using your legal name on Facebook, your account is at risk for deletion -- even if you have any one of a dozen legitimate reasons for not using your real name. This hardline policy doesn't just affect drag queens, as a graphic that has gone viral on Facebook points out:\n\nIndeed, back in 2010, Facebook founder Mark Zuckerberg famously said that having two names for yourself was \"an example of a lack of integrity.\" He has since softened his stance -- \"If you're always under the pressure of real identity, I think that is somewhat of a burden,\" Zuckerberg told Bloomberg earlier this year. \n\nBut Facebook hasn't changed its hardline position. Not even a high-level meeting with San Francisco politicians and representatives of the LGBT community in Facebook's home region produced any kind of shift in policy. Interest in Ello snowballed significantly after that meeting. \n\nSee also: Facebook to Meet With LGBT Community Over 'Real Names' Policy\n\nThis situation looks an awful lot like one of the biggest mistakes ever made by Friendster. That's the social network that launched in 2002 and could easily have become what Facebook is today -- indeed, Zuckerberg has admitted using it as a prototype -- before it tanked and was forced to sell to a Malaysian company that turned it into a gaming service.\n\nNow, recent articles on the history of Friendster tell us that the company's biggest mistake was not scaling properly. It didn't have the server architecture to handle the influx of interest. But those of us who were around in the Bay Area at the time, at the epicenter of Friendster's early adopters, remember it differently. \n\nIn 2003, Friendster had its own \"real names\" policy -- one that was significantly more draconian, but no less irksome, than Facebook's is now. Not only were you at risk for deletion if you didn't use your real name, you were at risk for deletion if you didn't use your real photo. People created profiles for bars, restaurants, landmarks, even concepts. All were deleted.\n\nIn a disastrous interview that should be required reading for every PR professional, Friendster founder Jonathan Abrams described people who used pictures of animals or babies on their profiles as \"smartasses.\" The week that interview published, pretty much everyone I knew on Friendster in the Bay Area moved their profile over to Mark Pincus' social network, Tribe.net -- the Ello of its day. \n\nSee also: Friendster Founder Tells His Side of the Story, 10 Years After Facebook\n\nShortly after that exodus, I ran into one of Friendster's top executives at a wedding. We chatted about the \"real profiles\" crisis, and he bristled at the notion that it could have any effect on the service whatsoever. \n\n\"We're trying to reach the mainstream, not your friends,\" he sniffed. \n\nWhich is of course a very logical, businesslike way of looking at things. You're talking millions of potential users versus a few hundred thousand early adopters. And surely those mainstream users would be perfectly happy to use their real pictures, right? To build your profile with anything else is just Bay Area weirdness.\n\nBut it turned out we weren't the only ones to chafe against such restrictions. As company after company has learned to their chagrin, in the social media age, hardcore power users rule. It's not just that their passion can make or break the image of a brand; it's also the fact that they are the canaries in the coal mine. \n\nAs Facebook has proved, millions of us like to use our pets or our kids or some beautiful scenery as our profile photo. It isn't weird or controversial at all. They're not being smartasses. They're being creative. \n\nSee also: In Facebook's First Article, Zuckerberg Admits 'Friendster Was a Model'\n\nFacebook, to its credit, isn't nearly as restrictive as Friendster was. It's doubtful Zuckerberg could have reached a billion users without allowing for a little creativity. But he too has drawn a line in the sand, against names that show a \"lack of integrity,\" and has stubbornly refused to shift on that, even in the face of evidence that it discriminates against the LGBT community, among others.\n\nThe Ello rebellion may be short-lived, or the tiny startup that created it may indeed be the Facebook killer that gives Zuckerberg nightmares. It almost doesn't matter. The hardcore power users have served notice. They're angry, restless, and ready to jump ship at the first opportunity -- so much so that they're sizing up every ship that sails by. \n\nIf that ship isn't Ello, it might be the next hot social network. There is no immutable law of the universe that says Facebook will keep its billion-plus monthly active users forever. Quite the opposite, in fact. Change is the only constant. The first shall be last. No company lives forever, especially not in the tech world. You can stay large but become irrelevant within a matter of years (just look at Microsoft.) \n\nIf Facebook is smart, it will understand this anger and reverse the real names policy. There are a lot of clever engineers at Facebook HQ in Menlo Park; they can figure out a fix that doesn't affect their precious datasets. Perhaps you can have a button that will allow users to ask for your real name but keep it hidden otherwise, in much the same way that you can now ask for a user's relationship status. \n\nBut they'd better do it fast. Ello may not work as an alternative today. But in Silicon Valley, tomorrow always comes faster than you expect.\n\nHave something to add to this story? Share it in the comments."},"shares":{"facebook":281,"twitter":1139,"linked_in":63,"google_plus":20,"total":1503},"comments_count":0,"image":"http://rack.2.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI3LzAzLzQ4NzQ2MTkyNy5iZTRiNC5qcGcKcAl0aHVtYgk5NTB4NTM0IwplCWpwZw/28c328b7/d1a/487461927.jpg","responsive_images":[{"image":"http://rack.1.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI3LzAzLzQ4NzQ2MTkyNy5iZTRiNC5qcGcKcAl0aHVtYgk2Mzh4MzY4IwplCWpwZw/82f49372/d1a/487461927.jpg","query":true,"size":"638x368#"},{"image":"http://rack.3.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI3LzAzLzQ4NzQ2MTkyNy5iZTRiNC5qcGcKcAl0aHVtYgkxMjc2eDczNiMKZQlqcGc/8f1efc55/d1a/487461927.jpg","query":"(min-resolution: 1.5dppx)","size":"1276x736#"},{"image":"http://rack.0.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI3LzAzLzQ4NzQ2MTkyNy5iZTRiNC5qcGcKcAl0aHVtYgkzNTZ4MjA1IwplCWpwZw/a3f9463d/d1a/487461927.jpg","query":"(max-width: 1160px)","size":"356x205#"},{"image":"http://rack.3.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI3LzAzLzQ4NzQ2MTkyNy5iZTRiNC5qcGcKcAl0aHVtYgk3MTJ4NDEwIwplCWpwZw/72de74b0/d1a/487461927.jpg","query":"(max-width: 1160px) and (min-resolution: 1.5dppx)","size":"712x410#"},{"image":"http://rack.2.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI3LzAzLzQ4NzQ2MTkyNy5iZTRiNC5qcGcKcAl0aHVtYgkyODB4MTU3IwplCWpwZw/eb880a2c/d1a/487461927.jpg","query":"(max-width: 480px)","size":"280x157#"},{"image":"http://rack.0.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI3LzAzLzQ4NzQ2MTkyNy5iZTRiNC5qcGcKcAl0aHVtYgk1NjB4MzE0IwplCWpwZw/d507058d/d1a/487461927.jpg","query":"(max-width: 480px) and (min-resolution: 1.5dppx)","size":"560x314#"}],"short_url":"http://on.mash.to/1rpylWC","choice":false,"spotlight":false,"shortcode_data":{"see_also":[{"data-url":"http://mashable.com/2014/09/25/whats-the-deal-with-ello/"},{"data-url":"http://mashable.com/2014/09/16/facebook-name-restrictions/"},{"data-url":"http://mashable.com/2014/02/03/jonathan-abrams-friendster-facebook/"},{"data-url":"http://mashable.com/2012/05/16/facebook-first-friendster/"}],"wp_shortcode_manager":[{}]},"excerpt":"The Ello rebellion may be short-lived, or the tiny startup that created it may indeed be the Facebook killer that gives Zuckerberg nightmares.","show_sponsorship":true,"channel":"Social Media","channel_link":"http://mashable.com/social-media/"},{"_id":"542617bab05f9d542400170f","id":"2014/09/26/ello-founder-talks-facebook-business","title":"Ello Cofounder Doesn't Think Facebook Is a Social Network","title_tag":null,"author":"Karissa Bell","post_date":"2014-09-27T01:49:37+00:00","post_date_rfc":"Sat, 27 Sep 2014 01:49:37 +0000","sort_key":"1xxHH2","link":"http://mashable.com/2014/09/26/ello-founder-talks-facebook-business/","content":{"plain":"Ello, the independent, invitation-only and ad-free social network that went viral almost overnight, is often compared to Facebook. Indeed, the still-nascent social network has already gained a reputation as the \"anti-Facebook.\"\n\nBut Ello cofounder Paul Budnitz doesn't put much stock in those comparisons -- in part because he thinks Facebook's users have become so commoditized that the platform stopped being a true social network long ago.\n\n\"The advertisers are the customer and the user is the product that's being bought and sold,\" he told Mashable. \"We don't see ourselves competing with them, because what we're doing feels so different.\"\n\nSee also: If Not Ello, Something Else: Facebook's 'Real Names' Policy Could Turn It Into Friendster\n\nLet's be clear: Ello's existing features aren't much different than those of any other social network. But part of what sets it apart -- and what has helped fuel its sudden exponential growth -- is the founders' adamant dedication to keeping the site free of ads. They even wrote a lengthy manifesto that ends with this declaration: \"You are not a product.\"\n\nBut just because Budnitz and his cofounders see no place for advertising on their site doesn't mean they don't want to make money. In fact, the company raised $435,000 in VC funding prior to its recent explosive growth. \n\nAnd given the recent buzz, it's certainly not unreasonable to think the company stands to raise much more than that in its next round of funding. \n\nAdditionally, as others have pointed out, when investors are involved, they expect companies to have a business model. So while advertising may seem like a forgone conclusion to some onlookers, Budnitz said this isn't the case. In fact, he insists there is another-- and better -- way.\n\nRather than ads, they plan to go with the freemium model app makers are increasingly adopting: Offer core service for free, and additional, \"premium\" features at a cost.\n\nBudnitz is quick to point out that those features, which may include the ability to create one profile for your personal life and one professional identity, are meant to appeal only to a small subset of users who will be able to unlock them by paying \"a couple of dollars.\"\n\n\"We want to make a successful business that makes money, but it doesn't have to be a $30 billion company,\" he said.\n\nBut what about those pesky investors who may have very different expectations? Not the case, he said, pointing out that Ello's founders own the majority of its stock. \n\n\"There's no one telling us what to do.\"\n\nHave something to add to this story? Share it in the comments."},"shares":{"facebook":230,"twitter":1563,"linked_in":160,"google_plus":33,"total":1986},"comments_count":0,"image":"http://rack.0.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI3LzUwL3BhdWxiZWxsby5jMTU2Ny5qcGcKcAl0aHVtYgk5NTB4NTM0IwplCWpwZw/1d739092/99e/paul-b-ello.jpg","responsive_images":[{"image":"http://rack.1.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI3LzUwL3BhdWxiZWxsby5jMTU2Ny5qcGcKcAl0aHVtYgk2Mzh4MzY4IwplCWpwZw/c5867558/99e/paul-b-ello.jpg","query":true,"size":"638x368#"},{"image":"http://rack.3.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI3LzUwL3BhdWxiZWxsby5jMTU2Ny5qcGcKcAl0aHVtYgkxMjc2eDczNiMKZQlqcGc/3350ad2b/99e/paul-b-ello.jpg","query":"(min-resolution: 1.5dppx)","size":"1276x736#"},{"image":"http://rack.1.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI3LzUwL3BhdWxiZWxsby5jMTU2Ny5qcGcKcAl0aHVtYgkzNTZ4MjA1IwplCWpwZw/d0563d0e/99e/paul-b-ello.jpg","query":"(max-width: 1160px)","size":"356x205#"},{"image":"http://rack.2.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI3LzUwL3BhdWxiZWxsby5jMTU2Ny5qcGcKcAl0aHVtYgk3MTJ4NDEwIwplCWpwZw/7f05b8d7/99e/paul-b-ello.jpg","query":"(max-width: 1160px) and (min-resolution: 1.5dppx)","size":"712x410#"},{"image":"http://rack.3.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI3LzUwL3BhdWxiZWxsby5jMTU2Ny5qcGcKcAl0aHVtYgkyODB4MTU3IwplCWpwZw/fd2f4f63/99e/paul-b-ello.jpg","query":"(max-width: 480px)","size":"280x157#"},{"image":"http://rack.1.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI3LzUwL3BhdWxiZWxsby5jMTU2Ny5qcGcKcAl0aHVtYgk1NjB4MzE0IwplCWpwZw/3f5083c2/99e/paul-b-ello.jpg","query":"(max-width: 480px) and (min-resolution: 1.5dppx)","size":"560x314#"}],"short_url":"http://on.mash.to/1Bjewmp","choice":false,"spotlight":false,"shortcode_data":{"see_also":[{"data-slug":"ello-facebook/"}],"wp_shortcode_manager":[{}]},"excerpt":"Ello cofounder Paul Budnitz on what's next for the anti-Facebook and how the private social network can turn a profit without advertising.","show_sponsorship":true,"channel":"Social Media","channel_link":"http://mashable.com/social-media/"},{"_id":"5424cea097b2f81e94000412","id":"2014/09/25/whats-the-deal-with-ello","title":"What's Up With Ello, the Anti-Facebook Social Network?","title_tag":null,"author":"Karissa Bell","post_date":"2014-09-26T02:25:25+00:00","post_date_rfc":"Fri, 26 Sep 2014 02:25:25 +0000","sort_key":"1xxlV0","link":"http://mashable.com/2014/09/25/whats-the-deal-with-ello/","content":{"plain":"By now, you've probably heard something about Ello, the ad-free, invite-only, independent social network that has seemingly gone viral over the last week.\n\nThe ad-free social network has quickly -- and somewhat inexplicably -- gained a reputation for being the \"anti-Facebook.\" Which is odd, because new users tend to boast on Facebook about having scored an invite to the service.\n\nSee also: 12 Facebook Statuses You Need to Retire\n\nWhile it's not clear what's behind the site's sudden surge in popularity (it launched in March to little fanfare), several reports have linked the rise of Ello to the recent firestorm caused by Facebook's so-called real name policy. \n\nFacebook's policy, which requires all users to go by their legal name on the social network, has been in place for some time -- but came under fire earlier this month as several drag performers and LGBT activists spoke out after being locked out of their accounts for not using their legal names. \n\nThe furor resulted in several San Francisco city officials getting involved -- and, eventually, a meeting at Facebook HQ. But though Facebook agreed to temporarily give individuals affected by the policy back their accounts, the social network has so far not changed their rules. \n\nThis has apparently caused some in the LGBT community to move to Ello, which allows users to identify themselves by any name they want.\n\n\"We believe a social network can be a tool for empowerment,\" Ello'smanifesto proclaims. \"Not a tool to deceive, coerce, and manipulate \u2014 but a place to connect, create, and celebrate life. You are not a product.\"\n\nThe site itself is like a cross between Twitter and Tumblr though with more limited features. Users can post status updates, photos and GIFs and comment on their friends' posts. There is a search tool to find the people you know though it's been buggy and unreliable in our testing.\n\nThe creators have a long list of new features, including mobile apps and more privacy settings, they say are in the works. But the timing of those updates is unclear.\n\nMeanwhile, the sudden popularity has fueled massive interest in the fledgling social network. Reports have surfaced claiming Ello is receiving anywhere from 4,000 to more than 30,000 requests an hour. \n\nWhile these numbers have been reported in a number of publications, it doesn't appear they have been independently verified. Still, the network apparently received so many requests that it had to temporarily limit users' abilities to send them Thursday.\n\nSo, someone literally sold an Ello invite for $500 on ebay. DO NOT PARTAKE IN THIS FOOLISHNESS :: http://t.co/Cb2R9s8EbM\u2014 CacheFlowe (@cacheflowe) September 24, 2014\n\nThe site's more enterprising users are taking advantage of the situation -- as dozens of beta invites have cropped up on eBay, with prices ranging anywhere from $5 to $150. \n\nIt's impossible to say whether Ello is the next big thing or just another passing fad -- but it has definitely succeeded in getting the Internet's attention.\n\nHave something to add to this story? Share it in the comments."},"shares":{"twitter":2078,"linked_in":405,"facebook":2884,"google_plus":172,"pinterest":7,"total":5546},"comments_count":0,"image":"http://rack.3.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI2LzllL2VsbG8uN2RiNTkuanBnCnAJdGh1bWIJOTUweDUzNCMKZQlqcGc/d1de0fcc/8e1/ello.jpg","responsive_images":[{"image":"http://rack.3.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI2LzllL2VsbG8uN2RiNTkuanBnCnAJdGh1bWIJNjM4eDM2OCMKZQlqcGc/4bf22420/8e1/ello.jpg","query":true,"size":"638x368#"},{"image":"http://rack.1.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI2LzllL2VsbG8uN2RiNTkuanBnCnAJdGh1bWIJMTI3Nng3MzYjCmUJanBn/bc982c8b/8e1/ello.jpg","query":"(min-resolution: 1.5dppx)","size":"1276x736#"},{"image":"http://rack.3.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI2LzllL2VsbG8uN2RiNTkuanBnCnAJdGh1bWIJMzU2eDIwNSMKZQlqcGc/567d690d/8e1/ello.jpg","query":"(max-width: 1160px)","size":"356x205#"},{"image":"http://rack.3.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI2LzllL2VsbG8uN2RiNTkuanBnCnAJdGh1bWIJNzEyeDQxMCMKZQlqcGc/287da99e/8e1/ello.jpg","query":"(max-width: 1160px) and (min-resolution: 1.5dppx)","size":"712x410#"},{"image":"http://rack.1.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI2LzllL2VsbG8uN2RiNTkuanBnCnAJdGh1bWIJMjgweDE1NyMKZQlqcGc/8d49e03d/8e1/ello.jpg","query":"(max-width: 480px)","size":"280x157#"},{"image":"http://rack.0.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI2LzllL2VsbG8uN2RiNTkuanBnCnAJdGh1bWIJNTYweDMxNCMKZQlqcGc/78520b34/8e1/ello.jpg","query":"(max-width: 480px) and (min-resolution: 1.5dppx)","size":"560x314#"}],"short_url":"http://on.mash.to/1qzBv6c","choice":false,"spotlight":false,"shortcode_data":{"see_also":[{"data-slug":"facebook-statuses-to-retire"}],"wp_shortcode_manager":[{}]},"excerpt":"The bizarreness that is Ello.","show_sponsorship":true,"channel":"Tech","channel_link":"http://mashable.com/tech/"},{"_id":"54248aaa97b2f8150900045f","id":"2014/09/25/hyperlapse-selfie","title":"How to Snap the Perfect Hyperlapse Selfie","title_tag":null,"author":"Kyli Singh","post_date":"2014-09-25T21:35:24+00:00","post_date_rfc":"Thu, 25 Sep 2014 21:35:24 +0000","sort_key":"1xxhjA","link":"http://mashable.com/2014/09/25/hyperlapse-selfie/","content":{"plain":"Selfies just got a whole lot fancier.\n\nUntil now, we could only shoot with the rear-facing camera on Instagram's popular time-lapse video app, Hyperlapse. With the app's new front-facing camera option, selfies will never be the same. Now you can record what the company calls a \"selfielapse\" with the touch of a button.\n\nSee also: 9 Flashy Camera Accessories for the iPhone 6\n\nIf you're wondering how the new feature works, you're in the right place. Below, we'll walk you through six steps to help you take a great selfielapse.\r\n1. Download Hyperlapse.\n\nHyperlapse is a free app that is only available for iOS devices. If you haven't already, download the app by clicking here.\r\n2. Launch Hyperlapse.\n\n3. Tap the camera-switch button.\n\nTap the circular button at the bottom-right of the screen to switch between the rear-facing camera and front-facing camera. When the camera flips, you'll see \"Selfielapse\" and \"Hyperlapse\" appear on the screen to let you know which mode you're in.\n\nPro tip: Another way to toggle between the rear-facing and front-facing cameras is to swipe horizontally on the screen.\n\nNote that when you begin recording, you do not have the option to switch between \"Selfielapse\" and \"Hyperlapse.\"\r\n4. Push record.\n\nSelfielapse works well with moving backgrounds, such as cars driving past and people walking behind you. It's also great for showing a process from beginning to end, such as putting on makeup.\n\nWhen you're ready to record, tap the circular white button at the bottom of the screen. Don't worry about a little camera shake here and there -- the app automatically stabilizes and smooths out videos.\n\nTo stop recording, push the red circular button.\r\n5. Select time-lapse speed.\n\nWhen you've finished recording, editing features will pop up on your screen. A slider will appear at the bottom of the screen that lets you adjust the speed of the video. It ranges from 1x to 12x -- 1x being the slowest speed, and 12x being the fastest speed.\n\nSee the examples below:\n\nIf you want to edit your video at a later time, tap the red \"X\" and select \"Edit Later.\" To access your \"Edit Later\" videos, tap the blue circle on the record screen.\n\nIf you want to delete your video, tap the red \"X\" and select \"Delete Hyperlapse.\"\r\n6. Save and post to Instagram or Facebook.\r\nWhen you're finished editing, tap the green check at the top-right corner of the screen. The app will automatically save the video to your phone's camera roll. After this, the app will conveniently ask you if you want to share your video on Instagram or Facebook.\n\nHave something to add to this story? Share it in the comments."},"shares":{"twitter":1323,"facebook":222,"linked_in":84,"google_plus":23,"stumble_upon":45,"pinterest":2,"total":1699},"comments_count":0,"image":"http://rack.2.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI2L2UzL1NlbGZpZWxhcHNlLjdhOGUxLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTk1MHg1MzQjCmUJanBn/f80a377a/885/Selfielapse-2-1.jpg","responsive_images":[{"image":"http://rack.3.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI2L2UzL1NlbGZpZWxhcHNlLjdhOGUxLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTYzOHgzNjgjCmUJanBn/396d4853/885/Selfielapse-2-1.jpg","query":true,"size":"638x368#"},{"image":"http://rack.0.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI2L2UzL1NlbGZpZWxhcHNlLjdhOGUxLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTEyNzZ4NzM2IwplCWpwZw/48b49244/885/Selfielapse-2-1.jpg","query":"(min-resolution: 1.5dppx)","size":"1276x736#"},{"image":"http://rack.0.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI2L2UzL1NlbGZpZWxhcHNlLjdhOGUxLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTM1NngyMDUjCmUJanBn/a178ddf4/885/Selfielapse-2-1.jpg","query":"(max-width: 1160px)","size":"356x205#"},{"image":"http://rack.3.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI2L2UzL1NlbGZpZWxhcHNlLjdhOGUxLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTcxMng0MTAjCmUJanBn/6237fe67/885/Selfielapse-2-1.jpg","query":"(max-width: 1160px) and (min-resolution: 1.5dppx)","size":"712x410#"},{"image":"http://rack.1.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI2L2UzL1NlbGZpZWxhcHNlLjdhOGUxLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTI4MHgxNTcjCmUJanBn/1d61d25e/885/Selfielapse-2-1.jpg","query":"(max-width: 480px)","size":"280x157#"},{"image":"http://rack.1.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI2L2UzL1NlbGZpZWxhcHNlLjdhOGUxLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTU2MHgzMTQjCmUJanBn/0b91b2cd/885/Selfielapse-2-1.jpg","query":"(max-width: 480px) and (min-resolution: 1.5dppx)","size":"560x314#"}],"short_url":"http://on.mash.to/1Bc7CPR","choice":false,"spotlight":false,"shortcode_data":{"see_also":[{"data-url":"http://mashable.com/2014/09/19/iphone-6-camera-accessories/"}],"wp_shortcode_manager":[{}]},"excerpt":"Selfies just got a whole lot fancier. Here's how to snap a great Hyperlapse selfie, dubbed \"selfielapse.\"","show_sponsorship":true,"channel":"Social Media","channel_link":"http://mashable.com/social-media/"},{"_id":"54245b3512d2cd099100002b","id":"2014/09/25/instagram-hyperlapse-selfies","title":"Time-Lapse Selfies Are Now a Thing, Courtesy of Instagram's Hyperlapse","title_tag":null,"author":"Karissa Bell","post_date":"2014-09-25T18:12:53+00:00","post_date_rfc":"Thu, 25 Sep 2014 18:12:53 +0000","sort_key":"1xxeco","link":"http://mashable.com/2014/09/25/instagram-hyperlapse-selfies/","content":{"plain":"If there's one app that can be credited with the rise of the selfie, it's Instagram. But now the Facebook-owned photo app is introducing a new kind of selfie -- the \"selfielapse.\"\n\nHyperlapse, Instagram's newest standalone app for time-lapse videos, got its first major update Thursday that allows users to shoot videos from their iPhones' front-facing cameras.\n\nSee also: 20 Creative Hyperlapses From Instagram's New App\n\nThe updated app now has a small button next to the shutter that toggles between the front- and rear-facing cameras. Switching to the front camera will alert you that you are switching to \"selfielapse\" mode.\n\nTime-lapse selfie videos work the same way as videos shot with the rear camera in Hyperlapse -- begin recording and two timers begin. The first tracks how long your video is and the second tells you how long your final video will be when compressed to the default 6x playback speed.\n\nAs with non-selfie Hyperlapses, the final video is put through the app's stabilization process, so even those with the shakiest of hands will have a smooth final product.\n\nHyperlapse is Instagram's second standalone app. The first was direct messaging app called Bolt, which is still only available to Android users in a coupe of countries.\n\nHave something to add to this story? Share it in the comments."},"shares":{"facebook":254,"linked_in":152,"twitter":848,"google_plus":67,"pinterest":5,"stumble_upon":141,"total":1467},"comments_count":0,"image":"http://rack.2.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI1L2UzL1NlbGZpZWxhcHNlLjBmM2QxLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTk1MHg1MzQjCmUJanBn/32de89f5/b68/Selfielapse-Thumbnail-new-1.jpg","responsive_images":[{"image":"http://rack.3.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI1L2UzL1NlbGZpZWxhcHNlLjBmM2QxLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTYzOHgzNjgjCmUJanBn/e27a5d0b/b68/Selfielapse-Thumbnail-new-1.jpg","query":true,"size":"638x368#"},{"image":"http://rack.3.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI1L2UzL1NlbGZpZWxhcHNlLjBmM2QxLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTEyNzZ4NzM2IwplCWpwZw/c3d7c8c6/b68/Selfielapse-Thumbnail-new-1.jpg","query":"(min-resolution: 1.5dppx)","size":"1276x736#"},{"image":"http://rack.2.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI1L2UzL1NlbGZpZWxhcHNlLjBmM2QxLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTM1NngyMDUjCmUJanBn/0848b42d/b68/Selfielapse-Thumbnail-new-1.jpg","query":"(max-width: 1160px)","size":"356x205#"},{"image":"http://rack.2.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI1L2UzL1NlbGZpZWxhcHNlLjBmM2QxLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTcxMng0MTAjCmUJanBn/dc734aea/b68/Selfielapse-Thumbnail-new-1.jpg","query":"(max-width: 1160px) and (min-resolution: 1.5dppx)","size":"712x410#"},{"image":"http://rack.2.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI1L2UzL1NlbGZpZWxhcHNlLjBmM2QxLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTI4MHgxNTcjCmUJanBn/9e6ac35b/b68/Selfielapse-Thumbnail-new-1.jpg","query":"(max-width: 480px)","size":"280x157#"},{"image":"http://rack.0.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI1L2UzL1NlbGZpZWxhcHNlLjBmM2QxLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTU2MHgzMTQjCmUJanBn/c63098dc/b68/Selfielapse-Thumbnail-new-1.jpg","query":"(max-width: 480px) and (min-resolution: 1.5dppx)","size":"560x314#"}],"short_url":"http://on.mash.to/1qyZYc0","choice":false,"spotlight":false,"shortcode_data":{"see_also":[{"data-slug":"instagram-hyperlapse/"}],"wp_shortcode_manager":[{}]},"excerpt":"The selfielapses are coming.","show_sponsorship":true,"channel":"Social Media","channel_link":"http://mashable.com/social-media/"},{"_id":"5423644fb589e44d02000174","id":"2014/09/24/amazon-wish-list-hashtag","title":"You Can Now Add Items to Your Amazon Wish List With a Tweet","title_tag":null,"author":"Karissa Bell","post_date":"2014-09-25T00:39:30+00:00","post_date_rfc":"Thu, 25 Sep 2014 00:39:30 +0000","sort_key":"1xwXXw","link":"http://mashable.com/2014/09/24/amazon-wish-list-hashtag/","content":{"plain":"Twitter just became an excellent way to manage your holiday wish list.\n\nAmazon revealed a new shopping hashtag Wednesday that allows shoppers to automatically add items to their wish list with a tweet.\n\nSee also: 9 Breaking News Tweets That Changed Twitter Forever\n\nAfter sending a tweet containing the #AmazonWishList hashtag and a link to the item (or replying to a tweet containing an Amazon link), the MyAmazon Twitter account should reply with the status of the item, including when it gets added to your list, if it's out of stock and how you can buy it.\n\nReply to this tweet with #AmazonWishList to add this Dancing Groot to your Wish List http://t.co/yGtyvy4YEF pic.twitter.com/cIxASv9U4Z\u2014 MyAmazon (@MyAmazon) September 24, 2014\n\nThis is the second time Twitter has partnered with Amazon on a hashtag. Previously, the companies introduced #AmazonCart, which allows users to add items to their Amazon shopping cart. As with that hashtag, users who want to take advantage of #AmazonWishList will need to link their Amazon and Twitter accounts through their Amazon account settings.\n\nTwitter has been ramping up its experiments that put shopping and buying services in users' Twitter timelines in recent months.\n\nThe company confirmed it began testing a \"Buy now\" button earlier this year. A payments and shipping option also appeared later in some users settings menu, prompting speculation that the social network may be moving closer to launching a native shopping service.\n\nHave something to add to this story? Share it in the comments."},"shares":{"twitter":1515,"facebook":335,"linked_in":275,"google_plus":62,"pinterest":5,"stumble_upon":66,"total":2258},"comments_count":0,"image":"http://rack.0.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI1LzhiL0hhc2h0YWdBbWF6LmZkNzIzLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTk1MHg1MzQjCmUJanBn/a639ab11/149/Hashtag-Amazon-Thumb.jpg","responsive_images":[{"image":"http://rack.3.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI1LzhiL0hhc2h0YWdBbWF6LmZkNzIzLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTYzOHgzNjgjCmUJanBn/2763a6bf/149/Hashtag-Amazon-Thumb.jpg","query":true,"size":"638x368#"},{"image":"http://rack.3.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI1LzhiL0hhc2h0YWdBbWF6LmZkNzIzLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTEyNzZ4NzM2IwplCWpwZw/bc4f344d/149/Hashtag-Amazon-Thumb.jpg","query":"(min-resolution: 1.5dppx)","size":"1276x736#"},{"image":"http://rack.1.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI1LzhiL0hhc2h0YWdBbWF6LmZkNzIzLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTM1NngyMDUjCmUJanBn/1cf6482c/149/Hashtag-Amazon-Thumb.jpg","query":"(max-width: 1160px)","size":"356x205#"},{"image":"http://rack.3.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI1LzhiL0hhc2h0YWdBbWF6LmZkNzIzLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTcxMng0MTAjCmUJanBn/feed9c44/149/Hashtag-Amazon-Thumb.jpg","query":"(max-width: 1160px) and (min-resolution: 1.5dppx)","size":"712x410#"},{"image":"http://rack.3.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI1LzhiL0hhc2h0YWdBbWF6LmZkNzIzLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTI4MHgxNTcjCmUJanBn/58219e34/149/Hashtag-Amazon-Thumb.jpg","query":"(max-width: 480px)","size":"280x157#"},{"image":"http://rack.3.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI1LzhiL0hhc2h0YWdBbWF6LmZkNzIzLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTU2MHgzMTQjCmUJanBn/4784ac38/149/Hashtag-Amazon-Thumb.jpg","query":"(max-width: 480px) and (min-resolution: 1.5dppx)","size":"560x314#"}],"short_url":"http://on.mash.to/1mtiuqY","choice":false,"spotlight":false,"shortcode_data":{"see_also":[{"data-url":"http://mashable.com/2013/10/31/twitter-news/"}],"wp_shortcode_manager":[{}]},"excerpt":"Amazon revealed a new shopping hashtag Wednesday that allows shoppers to automatically add items to their wish list with a tweet.","show_sponsorship":true,"channel":"Social Media","channel_link":"http://mashable.com/social-media/"},{"_id":"542330cbb589e4542000092c","id":"2014/09/24/apple-ios-8-twitter-reaction","title":"The Collective Twitter Freakout That Was the iOS 8.0.1 Update","title_tag":null,"author":"Rex Santus","post_date":"2014-09-24T20:59:36+00:00","post_date_rfc":"Wed, 24 Sep 2014 20:59:36 +0000","sort_key":"1xwVWE","link":"http://mashable.com/2014/09/24/apple-ios-8-twitter-reaction/","content":{"plain":"Less than a week after releasing iOS 8, Apple pushed out iOS 8.0.1 -- but the update did more harm than good. iPhone users reported issues with cell signal and Apple's Touch ID, and as a result, the company pulled the download.\n\nSee also: How to Downgrade From Apple's Fatally Flawed iOS 8.0.1 Back to iOS 8\n\nBut it was too late. Twitter had devolved into a collective panic. \n\njesus christ, why did i have to not wait on this iOS update.\u2014 Anthony Townsend (@anthonymobile) September 24, 2014\n\nWarning, the iOS 8.0.1 update will cause U2 to move into your spare room. #iOS8\u2014 HAL 9000 (@HAL9000_) September 24, 2014\n\nfirst #Bendghazi, now... MT @jsnell: Apple has pulled the 8.0.1 update. Un-updated iPhone 6 Plus is now reporting that iOS 8.0 is up to date\u2014 daveweigel (@daveweigel) September 24, 2014\n\n#tbt to when my phone was a phone\u2014 taylor hatmaker (@tayhatmaker) September 24, 2014\n\nWhile Apple is removing things like iOS 8.0.1 and U2, I'd also like to nominate Apple Maps and Newsstand.\u2014 John Dickerson (@jdickerson) September 24, 2014\n\niOS8 Twitter is the worst Twitter.\u2014 Pawe\u0142 Morski (@Pawelmorski) September 24, 2014\n\nIn the future it will be updated to iOS 8.0.1 and now I can\u2019t get into my house or turn my lights on, and I\u2019m not sure my heart is beating\u2014 Tom Warren (@tomwarren) September 24, 2014\n\nUpdated to iOS 8.0.1 and it bent my phone.\u2014 Sean Percival (@Percival) September 24, 2014\n\nThe irony of a Health fix that kills iOS 8\u2014 Federico Viticci (@viticci) September 24, 2014\n\nRIP iOS 8.0.1 1:00PM-1:30PM\u2014 Alex Soto (@dalexsoto) September 24, 2014\n\nHave something to add to this story? Share it in the comments."},"shares":{"linked_in":74,"facebook":598,"google_plus":18,"twitter":1415,"pinterest":1,"total":2106},"comments_count":0,"image":"http://rack.1.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI0LzhkL2lvczh0d2l0dGVyLjljMTIyLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTk1MHg1MzQjCmUJanBn/3c4d61bd/3c7/ios8-twitter1.jpg","responsive_images":[{"image":"http://rack.1.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI0LzhkL2lvczh0d2l0dGVyLjljMTIyLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTYzOHgzNjgjCmUJanBn/7a1d339d/3c7/ios8-twitter1.jpg","query":true,"size":"638x368#"},{"image":"http://rack.2.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI0LzhkL2lvczh0d2l0dGVyLjljMTIyLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTEyNzZ4NzM2IwplCWpwZw/2b6b1613/3c7/ios8-twitter1.jpg","query":"(min-resolution: 1.5dppx)","size":"1276x736#"},{"image":"http://rack.2.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI0LzhkL2lvczh0d2l0dGVyLjljMTIyLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTM1NngyMDUjCmUJanBn/622eedc8/3c7/ios8-twitter1.jpg","query":"(max-width: 1160px)","size":"356x205#"},{"image":"http://rack.2.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI0LzhkL2lvczh0d2l0dGVyLjljMTIyLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTcxMng0MTAjCmUJanBn/25f7d6a0/3c7/ios8-twitter1.jpg","query":"(max-width: 1160px) and (min-resolution: 1.5dppx)","size":"712x410#"},{"image":"http://rack.0.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI0LzhkL2lvczh0d2l0dGVyLjljMTIyLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTI4MHgxNTcjCmUJanBn/b8e0822d/3c7/ios8-twitter1.jpg","query":"(max-width: 480px)","size":"280x157#"},{"image":"http://rack.3.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI0LzhkL2lvczh0d2l0dGVyLjljMTIyLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTU2MHgzMTQjCmUJanBn/3f72cc9c/3c7/ios8-twitter1.jpg","query":"(max-width: 480px) and (min-resolution: 1.5dppx)","size":"560x314#"}],"short_url":"http://on.mash.to/1mtc4It","choice":false,"spotlight":false,"shortcode_data":{"see_also":[{"data-url":"http://mashable.com/2014/09/24/how-to-downgrade-ios-8-0-1/"}],"wp_shortcode_manager":[{}]},"excerpt":"Cue the witty banter.","show_sponsorship":true,"channel":"Social Media","channel_link":"http://mashable.com/social-media/"},{"_id":"54223afab589e465a60007ca","id":"2014/09/23/2030-photo-challenge-roundup","title":"Things We Still Want to See in the Year 2030","title_tag":null,"author":"Annie Park","post_date":"2014-09-24T03:30:54+00:00","post_date_rfc":"Wed, 24 Sep 2014 03:30:54 +0000","sort_key":"1xwEdE","link":"http://mashable.com/2014/09/23/2030-photo-challenge-roundup/","content":{"plain":"From September 21 to 22, our fifth annual Social Good Summit was held in New York City. Leaders in technology, business and social good came together to address the challenges our world faces and come up with solutions for the future.\n\nInspiring panels at the event covered topics ranging from millennials and sustainability to climate extremes.\n\nSee also: Why Millennials Are the World's Best Chance to Make Sustainability the New Normal\n\nTo go along with the theme, we challenged Mashable readers to share photos of things they hope will still exist in the year 2030. From flowers and bees to newspapers and ancient architecture, we saw a wide variety of submissions. \n\nScroll through our featured picks below, and check out all of the other submissions here. We'll announce our next Mashable Photo Challenge shortly.\n\n1. The Le Monde newspaper\n\n2. Tower church steeples\n\n3. The Bridgeport covered bridge\n\n4. Driving\n\n5. Wild mustangs\n\n6. Tigers\n\n7. Drying clothes outdoors\r\nSomething rustic and appealing about drying clothes outside rather than using a machine #MashPics pic.twitter.com/uylRqHGUTm\u2014 Dave Wheeler (@dwheelerau) September 21, 2014\n\n8. Roller coasters\r\n.@mashable we hope roller coasters are still around in 2030 #MashPics pic.twitter.com/Ey9vOtHPo0\u2014 Coaster101.com (@Coaster101) September 13, 2014\n\n9. Bagels\r\nIf bees cease to exist by 2030, will I lose both bagels AND orange marmalade? #mashpics @mashable pic.twitter.com/FvlQFrDJfC\u2014 Imr\u00e4n Ajmain (@ImranAjmain) September 21, 2014\n\nHave something to add to this story? Share it in the comments."},"shares":{"twitter":1140,"facebook":139,"google_plus":31,"linked_in":74,"total":1384},"comments_count":0,"image":"http://rack.0.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI0LzVkL3JvbGxlcmNvYXN0LjZhMThjLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTk1MHg1MzQjCmUJanBn/d584dde0/50c/rollercoaster_time.jpg","responsive_images":[{"image":"http://rack.0.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI0LzVkL3JvbGxlcmNvYXN0LjZhMThjLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTYzOHgzNjgjCmUJanBn/a40c19c5/50c/rollercoaster_time.jpg","query":true,"size":"638x368#"},{"image":"http://rack.1.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI0LzVkL3JvbGxlcmNvYXN0LjZhMThjLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTEyNzZ4NzM2IwplCWpwZw/1627baaa/50c/rollercoaster_time.jpg","query":"(min-resolution: 1.5dppx)","size":"1276x736#"},{"image":"http://rack.1.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI0LzVkL3JvbGxlcmNvYXN0LjZhMThjLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTM1NngyMDUjCmUJanBn/4071295e/50c/rollercoaster_time.jpg","query":"(max-width: 1160px)","size":"356x205#"},{"image":"http://rack.2.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI0LzVkL3JvbGxlcmNvYXN0LjZhMThjLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTcxMng0MTAjCmUJanBn/83973f39/50c/rollercoaster_time.jpg","query":"(max-width: 1160px) and (min-resolution: 1.5dppx)","size":"712x410#"},{"image":"http://rack.3.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI0LzVkL3JvbGxlcmNvYXN0LjZhMThjLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTI4MHgxNTcjCmUJanBn/f5370ff3/50c/rollercoaster_time.jpg","query":"(max-width: 480px)","size":"280x157#"},{"image":"http://rack.2.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzI0LzVkL3JvbGxlcmNvYXN0LjZhMThjLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTU2MHgzMTQjCmUJanBn/2a896431/50c/rollercoaster_time.jpg","query":"(max-width: 480px) and (min-resolution: 1.5dppx)","size":"560x314#"}],"short_url":"http://on.mash.to/1vdOHCv","choice":false,"spotlight":false,"shortcode_data":{"see_also":[{"data-url":"http://mashable.com/2014/09/23/sustainability-makeover/"}],"wp_shortcode_manager":[{}]},"excerpt":"From flowers and bees to newspapers and ancient architecture, we saw a wide variety of submissions. ","show_sponsorship":true,"channel":"Social Media","channel_link":"http://mashable.com/social-media/","sponsored_by":"Climate Summit","sponsored_by_url":"http://mashable.com/climate/","show_sponsorship_in_new_col":true,"sponsor_utm":"?utm_cid=hp-s-e"},{"_id":"5420b1b5b589e44fda0008e2","id":"2014/09/22/twitter-app-how-to-find-drafts","title":"How to Find Your Drafts and Lists in Twitter's New iPhone App","title_tag":null,"author":"Karissa Bell","post_date":"2014-09-22T23:32:56+00:00","post_date_rfc":"Mon, 22 Sep 2014 23:32:56 +0000","sort_key":"1xwdPQ","link":"http://mashable.com/2014/09/22/twitter-app-how-to-find-drafts/","content":{"plain":"Twitter released an iOS 8 friendly update last week that included a new profile design and interactive notifications.\n\nBut although the most noticeable change was the revamped profiles, many users are unhappy with parts of the update -- largely because it changes the location of draft tweets and lists. \n\nLuckily, both are still accessible. Here's how to find them.\n\nSee also: 8 Awkward Times the Media Tried to Explain the Internet\n\nThe change users seem to be most confused by is drafts, whose new location in the iOS app is not immediately obvious. So much so, in fact, some users seem to think the folder has been removed entirely.\n\nSo how do I find my drafts on this new look Twitter app? If a tweet doesn't post does that mean I just have to keep doing it again?\u2014 Nick Duckworth (@nickyducky) September 22, 2014\n\nDid the drafts section disappear with the new update for the Twitter app? There's a game changing tweet that got stuck there this morning.\u2014 Lolita Covita (@laura_cov) September 22, 2014\n\nIn fact, there are now two ways to access your drafts in the iOS 8 Twitter app. The simplest is to hold down the compose icon in the top right corner of the app, which brings up your drafts folder, but you can also find drafts in Twitter's main compose menu under the quill icon in the bottom right corner of the app.\n\nFor anyone confused about where lists live in the new Twitter app: lists can be found under the settings menu on your profile page. From there, you'll see tabs for the lists you're subscribed to and the lists you're a member of.\n\nSimilarly, if you want to view another user's public lists, open the settings menu from their profile to display the lists they are members of and those they are subscribed to.\n\nHave something to add to this story? Share it in the comments."},"shares":{"twitter":1737,"facebook":303,"google_plus":50,"linked_in":108,"pinterest":3,"total":2201},"comments_count":0,"image":"http://rack.3.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzIyLzA0L1R3aXR0ZXJfUHJvLjVjODliLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTk1MHg1MzQjCmUJanBn/d051341b/ca4/Twitter_Profile.jpg","responsive_images":[{"image":"http://rack.1.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzIyLzA0L1R3aXR0ZXJfUHJvLjVjODliLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTYzOHgzNjgjCmUJanBn/93e6d2b5/ca4/Twitter_Profile.jpg","query":true,"size":"638x368#"},{"image":"http://rack.1.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzIyLzA0L1R3aXR0ZXJfUHJvLjVjODliLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTEyNzZ4NzM2IwplCWpwZw/68e46d14/ca4/Twitter_Profile.jpg","query":"(min-resolution: 1.5dppx)","size":"1276x736#"},{"image":"http://rack.0.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzIyLzA0L1R3aXR0ZXJfUHJvLjVjODliLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTM1NngyMDUjCmUJanBn/a9256137/ca4/Twitter_Profile.jpg","query":"(max-width: 1160px)","size":"356x205#"},{"image":"http://rack.1.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzIyLzA0L1R3aXR0ZXJfUHJvLjVjODliLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTcxMng0MTAjCmUJanBn/187537bb/ca4/Twitter_Profile.jpg","query":"(max-width: 1160px) and (min-resolution: 1.5dppx)","size":"712x410#"},{"image":"http://rack.0.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE0LzA5LzIyLzA0L1R3aXR0ZXJfUHJvLjVjODliLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTI4MHgxNTcjCmUJanBn/1d7a2c39/ca4/Twitter_Profile.jpg","query":"(max-width: 480px)","size":"280x157#"},{"im